arXiv:2412.10677v1 Announce Type: cross Abstract: Using data samples of 983.0~$m fb^{-1}$ and 427.9~$m fb^{-1}$ accumulated with the Belle and Belle~II detectors operating at the KEKB and SuperKEKB asymmetric-energy $e^+e^-$ colliders, singly Cabibbo-suppressed decays $\Xi_c^{+} 	o pK_{S}^{0}$, $\Xi_c^+ 	o \Lambda \pi^+$, and $\Xi_c^+ 	o \Sigma^{0} \pi^+$ are observed for the first time. The ratios of branching fractions of $\Xi_{c}^{+}	o p K_{S}^{0}$, $\Xi_{c}^{+}	o \Lambda \pi^{+}$, and $\Xi_{c}^{+}	o \Sigma^{0} \pi^{+}$ relative to that of $\Xi_c^+ 	o \Xi^- \pi^{+} \pi^{+}$ are measured to be  egin{equation}  rac{{\cal B}(\Xi_c^+ 	o pK_S^0)}{{\cal B}(\Xi_c^{+} 	o \Xi^{-} \pi^+ \pi^+)} = (2.47 \pm 0.16 \pm 0.07)\% 
otag, \end{equation}  egin{equation}  rac{{\cal B}(\Xi_c^+ 	o \Lambda \pi^+)}{{\cal B}(\Xi_c^{+} 	o \Xi^{-} \pi^+ \pi^+)} = (1.56 \pm 0.14 \pm 0.09)\% 
otag, \end{equation}  egin{equation}  rac{{\cal B}(\Xi_c^+ 	o \Sigma^0 \pi^+)}{{\cal B}(\Xi_c^{+} 	o \Xi^{-} \pi^+ \pi^+)} = (4.13 \pm 0.26 \pm 0.22)\% 
otag. \end{equation} Multiplying these values by the branching fraction of the normalization channel, ${\cal B}(\Xi_c^{+} 	o \Xi^{-} \pi^+\pi^+) = (2.9 \pm 1.3)\%$, the absolute branching fractions are determined to be  egin{equation} {\cal B}(\Xi_c^{+} 	o p K_{S}^{0}) = (7.16 \pm 0.46 \pm 0.20 \pm 3.21) 	imes 10^{-4} 
otag, \end{equation}  egin{equation} {\cal B}(\Xi_c^{+} 	o \Lambda \pi^+) = (4.52 \pm 0.41 \pm 0.26 \pm 2.03) 	imes 10^{-4} 
otag, \end{equation}  egin{equation} {\cal B}(\Xi_c^{+} 	o \Sigma^0 \pi^+) = (1.20 \pm 0.08 \pm 0.07 \pm 0.54) 	imes 10^{-3} 
otag. \end{equation} The first and second uncertainties above are statistical and systematic, respectively, while the third ones arise from the uncertainty in ${\cal B}(\Xi_c^{+} 	o \Xi^{-} \pi^{+} \pi^{+})$.

arXiv:2410.21383v2 Announce Type: replace Abstract: Collinear emission of $W$ bosons off a high-energy muon induces a large muon-neutrino component among the Parton Distribution Functions (PDFs) of a muon. In this paper we study the phenomenology related to the $
u_\mu$ PDF at future high-energy muon colliders. We examine total rates and differential distributions of the $e  ar{
u}_e$ and $W \gamma$ production processes, which receive a large, and often dominant, contribution from this PDF, allowing for a detailed experimental study. As a demonstration of the impact the $
u_\mu$ PDF could have for searches of new physics, we study the charged-current pair production of a couple of heavy states, components of a ${m SU}(2)_L$ doublet. In both $e ar{
u}_e$ production and charged-current pair production of heavy states, we compare results obtained using PDFs with those of a fixed-order simulation.
